INSERT INTO `couch_data_text` VALUES("10", "96", "<h3>\r\n	Stories of our clients</h3>\r\n<article class=\"story\" id=\"story-1\" name=\"story-1\">\r\n	<h4>\r\n		Keeping going - <em>Ashley, 16</em></h4>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Ashley was referred to RAYS after experiencing a sexual assault at the age of 10, and winding her way through a number of professionals and programs. Ashley struggled with change, having lacked consistency with who she worked with and being obligated to tell her story again and again to different people.</p>\r\n	<p class=\"quote-text\">\r\n		Battling with severe depression, Ashley was actively suicidal and had been hospitalized in the past.</p>\r\n	<blockquote class=\"quote-right\">\r\n		&ldquo;She was going through the impact of trauma, and not feeling supported by her family.&rdquo;</blockquote>\r\n	Her counselor noted that &ldquo;she was going through the impact of trauma, and not feeling supported by her family.&rdquo; Hearing from both peers and family the idea that she essentially had to &ldquo;deal with this on her own&rdquo;, getting the support that she needed from her mom in particular had proven to be a struggle.\r\n	<p>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p class=\"quote-text\">\r\n		When asked what was her biggest success in counseling with RAYS, she replied that &ldquo;she&rsquo;s alive still.&rdquo; Ashley credited much of that fact to the skills she had learned through counseling, not the least of which were journaling and free writing.</p>\r\n	<blockquote class=\"quote-left\">\r\n		...she replied that &ldquo;she&rsquo;s alive still.&rdquo;</blockquote>\r\n	Through writing and addressing the underlying belief structure she had developed around the trauma, Ashley has been able to better calm herself down when she is feeling reactive, and ultimately be more authentic in who she is.\r\n	<p>\r\n		&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Recently Ashley has continued to work on her communication, and to confront the difficulty she finds in being alone. She is taking initiative to overcome her depression and apathy, and her counselor has noted just how exciting it is &ldquo;starting to see her thrive, and really, not needing counseling anymore.&rdquo;</p>\r\n	<p class=\"asterisk-text\">\r\n		*Name changed for confidentiality purposes.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n", "Stories of our clients Keeping going - Ashley, 16 Ashley was referred to RAYS after experiencing a sexual assault at the age of 10, and winding her way through a number of professionals and programs. Ashley struggled with change, having lacked consistency with who she worked with and being obligated to tell her story again and again to different people. Battling with severe depression, Ashley was actively suicidal and had been hospitalized in the past. She was going through the impact of trauma, and not feeling supported by her family. Her counselor noted that she was going through the impact of trauma, and not feeling supported by her family. Hearing from both peers and family the idea that she essentially had to deal with this on her own, getting the support that she needed from her mom in particular had proven to be a struggle.  When asked what was her biggest success in counseling with RAYS, she replied that shes alive still. Ashley credited much of that fact to the skills she had learned through counseling, not the least of which were journaling and free writing. ...she replied that shes alive still. Through writing and addressing the underlying belief structure she had developed around the trauma, Ashley has been able to better calm herself down when she is feeling reactive, and ultimately be more authentic in who she is.  Recently Ashley has continued to work on her communication, and to confront the difficulty she finds in being alone. She is taking initiative to overcome her depression and apathy, and her counselor has noted just how exciting it is starting to see her thrive, and really, not needing counseling anymore. *Name changed for confidentiality purposes.");
